. Hi Pradeep,

Here is the code in example 40:
javascript
countryApp.controller('CountryListCtrl', function ($scope, countries){
  countries.list(function(countries) {
    $scope.countries = countries;
  });
});
Unfortunately this code uses the variable name countries for two different things, which might be confusing. Here's a version with two different names:
javascript
countryApp.controller('CountryListCtrl', function ($scope, countries){
  countries.list(function(countriesList) {
    $scope.countries = countriesList;
  });
});
The code you have uses the array notation for dependency injection, but only specifies $scope as a dependency, not countries. Here's code similar to yours to show what is missing:
javascript
countryApp.controller('CountryListCtrl', ['$scope', /* 'countries' should go here */ function ($scope, countries){
  countries.list(function(countriesList) {
    $scope.countries = countriesList;
  });
  console.log(countries);
}]);
You need to change your code to include countries as a dependency in the array, like this:
javascript
countryApp.controller('CountryListCtrl', ['$scope', 'countries', function ($scope, countries){
  countries.list(function(countriesList) {
    $scope.countries = countriesList;
  });
  console.log(countries);
}]);
Hope this helps. Good luck.
